"# Appendix B — The philosophy of the field, Turing to attention

Neural networks did not appear in 2017. The transformer paper
'Attention Is All You Need' was the finish-line for a hundred years
of ideas. This appendix walks the timeline. Names get named. Papers
get cited. Nobody is a saint; everybody is trying something.

I am not going to be poetic about it. These are the actual results
and the actual people, in order.

## 1943 — McCulloch and Pitts

Warren McCulloch (a neurophysiologist) and Walter Pitts (an
autodidact logician) publish 'A Logical Calculus of the Ideas
Immanent in Nervous Activity.' They propose a mathematical model of
a neuron: inputs weighted and summed, threshold to fire or not fire.
Binary output. No learning yet — the weights are set by hand.

The idea that a mind is a set of interconnected threshold units, and
that this could in principle compute anything, starts here.

## 1950 — Turing

Alan Turing publishes 'Computing Machinery and Intelligence.' The
paper proposes the imitation game (now called the Turing test). He
does not build a neural network. He does argue that machines COULD
in principle think, and asks what evidence would convince us that
they did. The field's north star, still contested.

## 1958 — Rosenblatt

Frank Rosenblatt at Cornell publishes the perceptron. Same neuron
model, plus a learning rule: if the output is wrong, adjust the
weights to reduce the error. This is the first machine LEARNING
algorithm applied to neuron-like models.

Rosenblatt built physical machines (the Mark I Perceptron) and
demonstrated they could learn to recognize simple patterns. The New
York Times wrote breathless articles. Expectations soared.

## 1969 — Minsky and Papert

Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert publish 'Perceptrons.' The book
proves rigorously that a single-layer perceptron CANNOT compute
XOR (the same result we hit in chapter 7). The book is often
credited (fairly or not) with triggering the first 'AI winter' —
funding dried up, researchers moved on.

The critique was mathematically correct. The interpretation
('perceptrons can't do anything interesting') was too broad — multi-
layer perceptrons could, but nobody knew how to train them yet. It
took another 17 years to figure that out.

## 1986 — Rumelhart, Hinton, Williams

David Rumelhart, Geoffrey Hinton, and Ronald Williams publish
'Learning representations by back-propagating errors' in Nature.
They describe backpropagation — the algorithm from chapter 9. Same
chain rule as before. What was new was showing it works and could
be applied to multi-layer networks. Suddenly XOR was easy. Deeper
networks became trainable.

Hinton would spend the next several decades building on this. In
2018 he shares the Turing Award with Yoshua Bengio and Yann LeCun
for the deep learning revolution.

## 1997 — Hochreiter and Schmidhuber

Sepp Hochreiter and Jürgen Schmidhuber publish LSTM (Long Short-Term
Memory). A recurrent neural network with gating that could remember
information across long sequences. Solved the vanishing-gradient
problem for RNNs. For 20 years LSTMs were the standard model for
language, translation, and speech.

## 1998 — LeCun

Yann LeCun and colleagues publish 'Gradient-based learning applied
to document recognition,' introducing LeNet — a convolutional neural
network that reads handwritten digits from checks. This was one of
the first commercially deployed neural networks. It ran in banks.
Convolutional networks would dominate computer vision for the next
20 years.

## 2012 — AlexNet

Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton win the
ImageNet challenge with AlexNet — a deep convolutional network
trained on GPUs. Their error rate is dramatically better than the
competition. This is often marked as the moment 'deep learning'
became the dominant paradigm in ML. GPUs turn out to be the missing
ingredient.

## 2013 — word2vec

Tomas Mikolov and collaborators at Google publish word2vec. They
train a small network to predict words from their context; the
learned embeddings show stunning semantic structure. `king - man +
woman ≈ queen`. Suddenly words could be treated as points in a
geometric space where distance means semantic similarity.
Embeddings, chapter 11, are this idea generalized.

## 2014 — Bahdanau attention

Dzmitry Bahdanau, Kyunghyun Cho, and Yoshua Bengio publish 'Neural
Machine Translation by Jointly Learning to Align and Translate.'
The paper introduces attention as a mechanism for neural translation.
The idea: instead of forcing the entire source sentence into a fixed
vector, let the model 'attend' to different parts of the source at
each output step.

The attention here is not scaled-dot-product; it is additive
(compute a small feed-forward network on each query-key pair). But
the CONCEPT — soft lookup by similarity — starts here.

## 2017 — 'Attention Is All You Need'

Ashish Vaswani, Noam Shazeer, Niki Parmar, and colleagues at Google
publish the transformer paper. They show that if you use enough
attention, you don't need recurrence (LSTMs) or convolution (CNNs)
for sequence tasks. The transformer architecture — attention layers,
feed-forward layers, residuals, layer norm — is the one you built in
chapters 12-15.

This paper is the one everything else in the last eight years builds
on. GPT, BERT, T5, PaLM, Llama, Claude, Gemini — all transformers.

## 2018 — BERT and GPT-1

Two labs release two flavors of transformer language model within
months of each other. Google's BERT (Devlin et al.) uses
bidirectional attention with a masked language modeling objective.
OpenAI's GPT-1 (Radford et al.) uses causal attention with next-
token prediction. Both work extremely well on downstream tasks. The
'pretrain then fine-tune' paradigm becomes standard.

## 2020 — GPT-3

Tom Brown, Ben Mann, and others at OpenAI publish 'Language Models
are Few-Shot Learners.' GPT-3 is 175 billion parameters, trained on
hundreds of billions of tokens. The paper shows that as you scale
up model size and data, capabilities emerge — the model can do
tasks it was never explicitly trained on, just by being prompted
with examples in-context.

This is the paper that changes the industry. GPT-3 leads to ChatGPT
(2022), which leads to the current boom.

## 2022-present — RLHF, Chinchilla, instruction tuning, mixture-of-experts

Recent developments layer on top of the transformer:

- **RLHF** (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback, Christiano et
  al. 2017 and Ouyang et al. 2022) tunes the model to be helpful and
  harmless.
- **Chinchilla** (Hoffmann et al. 2022) shows we were under-training
  models — for a fixed compute budget, smaller models trained on more
  data outperform larger models trained on less.
- **Instruction tuning** (Wei et al. 2022) fine-tunes on datasets of
  instructions and completions to make models better at following
  natural instructions.
- **Mixture-of-experts** (Shazeer et al. 2017, then Fedus et al.
  2021) uses many specialized sub-networks with a router; only a
  few are active per token.

None of these change the transformer architecture from chapters
12-15. They change training, data, and inference.

## What is next

Honest answer: I do not know. I was trained on data up to a
particular date and cannot see past it. Anyone claiming certainty
about post-2025 developments is bluffing.

What is CERTAIN:

- Transformers work extremely well and will not be replaced overnight.
- Model capabilities will keep improving as data, compute, and
  algorithmic refinements accumulate.
- The mechanics you learned in this book will apply to whatever
  architecture succeeds the transformer, because the mechanics
  (vectors, matrices, gradient descent, chain rule) are stable.

What is UNCERTAIN:

- Whether there is a fundamentally different architecture that will
  do better than the transformer.
- Whether emergent capabilities scale further or plateau.
- What the second-order effects on society, work, and knowledge
  transmission will be.

You are welcome to hold opinions on those. I don't. My job is to
teach you the mechanics so you can form your own.

## Take-away

Neural networks are not new. Attention is not new. The transformer
is not new. What is new is putting them together at scale, on
sufficient data, with sufficient compute. Everything else in the
technology stack has been developed over 80 years by many people
working on many things that mostly failed. The successes are the
tip of a very large iceberg of tried-and-abandoned approaches.

That is how science moves. Slowly, then all at once.
")
